<html><head><meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8"></head><body dir="auto"><div><p class="s4" style="text-align: start; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 21.600000381469727px;"><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px; background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);">RHS MEMORIES</span></p><p class="s4" style="text-align: start; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 21.600000381469727px;"><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px; background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);">Abe Hoffman</span></p><p class="s2" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 21.600000381469727px;"><span style="background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);"><span style="line-height: 21.600000381469727px; padding-left: 36px;">​</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">In the decades following graduation in 1956 I have attended a few reu</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">n</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">ions and would like to share my recollections. &nbsp;</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">In 1986 I attended the 30</span><span class="s5" style="line-height: 10.800000190734863px; vertical-align: super;">th</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">&nbsp;year reunion, and after waiting almost a year (give or take a couple of years), when the reunion booklet arrived it was quite an experience to finally receive it. &nbsp;The spelling and typographical errors were truly something to behold. &nbsp;Some names were misspelled almost beyond recognition. &nbsp;Maybe people scribbled their names so badly the company couldn’t read them clearly. &nbsp;Or maybe one could blame the LAUSD for the failure of its schools to teach could penmanship. &nbsp;Well, if one looks at all this in a certain way, maybe the booklet was really worth the twenty bucks charged for it. &nbsp;You have to look it over very carefully just to sort out the fun time from the mistakes, and perhaps that’s the way we are dealing with our lives as well, some sixty years later.</span></span></p><p class="s2" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 21.600000381469727px;"><span style="background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);"><span style="line-height: 21.600000381469727px; padding-left: 36px;">​</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">Walking into the ballroom in 1986, I immediately ran into someone I hadn’t seen since graduation. &nbsp;He recognized me at once and said, “It’s Hoffman! &nbsp;Still reading&nbsp;</span><span class="s6" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px; font-style: italic;">Mad&nbsp;</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">magazine?” &nbsp;I found it incredible that in a three-decade period that included the Vietnam War, the Pill, color TV, video recorders, the women’s liberation movement, two oil crises, and astronauts walking on the moon, not to mention computer, pages, cordless phones, and compact disks, this former&nbsp;</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">classmate could only measure the passage of time by asking me if I still read a magazine I had stopped reading in 1957.</span></span></p><p class="s2" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 21.600000381469727px;"><span style="background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);"><span style="line-height: 21.600000381469727px; padding-left: 36px;">​</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">Now, in the 21</span><span class="s5" style="line-height: 10.800000190734863px; vertical-align: super;">st</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">&nbsp;century, we’re online, on the internet, considering buying Viagra, texting instead of actually talking to someone, and talking to someone thousands of miles away as if that person was next door. &nbsp;</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">The 50</span><span class="s5" style="line-height: 10.800000190734863px; vertical-align: super;">th</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">&nbsp;reunion in 2006 was a lot of fun—reconnecting with classmates and sharing the experiences life had given them. &nbsp;Unfortunately, there was no 60</span><span class="s5" style="line-height: 10.800000190734863px; vertical-align: super;">th</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">&nbsp;reunion in 2016—not enough people still around, even with combining with classes from 1955 and 1957, to make the necessary minimum required by a restaurant to hold a get-together.</span></span></p><p class="s2" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 21.600000381469727px;"><span style="background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);"><span style="line-height: 21.600000381469727px; padding-left: 36px;">​</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">When I left RHS the last thing I thought I would get into was teaching school, given my rather negative experiences with so many of the RHS teachers. &nbsp;But my parents insisted I should go to college and, though RHS hadn’t really prepared me for it, I went to college—Los Angeles City College, knowing I wouldn’t have lasted a week at UCLA. &nbsp;Somehow</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">,</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">&nbsp;I survived two years at LACC, transferred to Cal State L.A. (or Los Angeles State College as it was then called), and became interested in history, mainly because of some excellent history professors there. &nbsp;When I got the B.A. in 1960 it seemed only natural to continue on to the M.A</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">.</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">&nbsp;program and pick up a teaching credential along the way</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">.</span></span></p><p class="s2" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 21.600000381469727px;"><span style="background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);"><span style="line-height: 21.600000381469727px; padding-left: 36px;">​</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">In 1962 I obtained a general secondary credential (aka “the license to steal”) and began teaching full-time at Hollenbeck Junior high, not much of a stretch into&nbsp;</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">adulthood as it turned out. &nbsp;A few teachers there couldn’t believe that I was now a colleague, but Miss Ida Crum welcomed me to the faculty and we became great friends. &nbsp;My parents didn’t move out of Boyle Heights until 1965, but I had my own apartment by then. &nbsp;Except for the period 1970-1974, when I made a really bad career move, I worked for the LAUSD until retiring in 1999. &nbsp;From 1974 to the present day I have also worked as an adjunct professor at Los Angeles Valley College.</span></span></p><p class="s2" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 21.600000381469727px;"><span style="background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);"><span style="line-height: 21.600000381469727px; padding-left: 36px;">​</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">Maybe I got into teaching because I needed to let students know that not all their teachers were so mean as some of the ones I knew as a student and also as a fellow teacher. &nbsp;For the most part I have enjoyed my time in the classroom, though there have been administrators who didn’t enjoy the fact that I was in the classroom!</span></span></p><p class="s2" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 21.600000381469727px;"><span style="background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);"><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">Only rarely have I run into RHS classmates</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">. &nbsp;Having lived in the San Fernando Valley since 1974, there was little opportunity to find former classmates, with one interesting exception. &nbsp;While teaching at Franklin High School in the 1980s, who should be there as a P.E. teacher but David&nbsp;</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">Perea</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">, last seen by me when he was in my 8</span><span class="s5" style="line-height: 10.800000190734863px; vertical-align: super;">th</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">&nbsp;grade U.S. History class at Hollenbeck some twenty years earlier. &nbsp;Then, in 2011, when I was invited to give a presentation at Roosevelt High on the history of Boyle Heights, David teaching there. &nbsp;We had a fascinating lunch in which I recalled Miss Crum as a great teacher, David recalled being in my History class,&nbsp;</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">David’s student teacher listening to David’s recollection, and a student in the student teacher’s class listening to four generations of Hollenbeck/Roosevelt history being told (though no doubt with some exaggerations and outright lying).</span></span></p><p class="s2" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 21.600000381469727px;"><span style="background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);"><span style="line-height: 21.600000381469727px; padding-left: 36px;">​</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">With the creation of websites such as LinkedIn and <a href="http://classmates.com">Classmates.com</a> there came the opportunity to connect with people I hadn’t heard of in ages. &nbsp;It’s regrettable that the LAUSD chose to have a company redo the individual school websites, because that company seems more interested in selling t-shirts and hats with logos than in attracting alumni and convincing them to join. I find there’s a hunger that kicks in when one reaches beyond the age of retirement to contact with those who shared the most intense period of life—childhood and adolescence. &nbsp;</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">Adult</span><span class="s3" style="line-height: 16.799999237060547px;">hood has its own rewards, but that early level of intensity can’t be forgotten.</span></span></p><p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 21.600000381469727px;"><a style="background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);"><font color="#000000">2</font></a></p><p class="s7" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; line-height: 1.2;"><span style="line-height: 21.600000381469727px; background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0);">&nbsp;</span></p><br>Sent from my iPad</div></body></html>